    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Convention Kiss</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Laura Louison letter disputes Nora Roberts's August 23 Op-Ed article on Vice Pres Al Gore's kiss of wife Tipper at Democratic National Convention; says action was shrewd political move</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Votes in a Kiss,'' by Nora Roberts (Op-Ed, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>I am aware that Ms. Roberts's books sell millions more copies than any book by Simone de Beauvoir. Yet I cannot but hope that women across America are not being drawn to Al Gore because he kissed his wife at the Democratic National Convention in what was clearly a shrewd political move.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Votes in a Kiss,'' by Nora Roberts (Op-Ed, Aug. 23):</p>
        <p>I am aware that Ms. Roberts's books sell millions more copies than any book by Simone de Beauvoir. Yet I cannot but hope that women across America are not being drawn to Al Gore because he kissed his wife at the Democratic National Convention in what was clearly a shrewd political move.</p>
        <p>By suggesting that ''a lot of us may pay more attention to Mr. Gore's words because of that quick, endearing and romantic impulse,'' Ms. Roberts does both men and women a great disservice.</p>
        <p>LAURA LOUISON  Swarthmore, Pa., Aug. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
